üåø budding and almost ready to split into Zettels
My note seedlings don&rsquo;t take root and branch off, with branches returning to a single point (the trunk of the tree). My note seedlings are, instead, rhizomes. The notes and ideas don&rsquo;t have one origin point. &ldquo;Branches can grow out of any spot towards any direction.&rdquo;1
‚ÄúRhizomes, however, do not function according to representation. Nothing in a rhizome represents something else. There are only connections.‚Äù2
An arborescent view of a digital garden would be that notes are, in a Platonic sense, trying to become their ideal self. The farther they are from that ideal state, the more they have branched off from the root of the tree. But in a rhizomatic garden, there is no ideal state to work towards.3
[[Explaining Deleuze with drum machines]] &#160;&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;
[[Deleuze and Guattari&rsquo;s A Thousand Plateaus: A Critical Introduction and Guide]] by [[Brent Adkins]]&#160;&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;
